  "text": "However, the question still remains unanswered as to how PIP 2 interacts with the C terminus of TRPC4 and -5 [CITATION_1] . Direct C-terminal PIP 2 interaction was demonstrated for the unique TRPC4α isoform [CITATION_2] . Truncation of the C-terminal TTRL motif of TRPC4α abolished PIP 2 -induced channel inhibition, entertaining the notion that binding of NHERF1 and PIP 2 to the C terminus stabilizes an inactive channel conformation [CITATION_3] . However, NHERF interaction was not linked to DAG sensitivity in the latter study.",
